The multiple tert-butyl groups, which are large and bulky, add significant steric hindrance and increase the molecular weight, causing an expected rise in the melting point. Each tert-butyl group could potentially add around +20°C to the melting point. The hydroxy group (-OH) can form hydrogen bonds, which typically increase melting points significantly, by around +100°C in this context because of the rigidity it adds to the structure. The N'-methylbenzenecarboximidamide moiety increases rigidity and potential for hydrogen bonding, adding another +30°C. Considering all these factors: Benzene base (+5.5), four tert-butyl groups (+80 in total), one hydroxy group (+100), and the N'-methylbenzenecarboximidamide moiety (+30), the predicted melting point adds up to 215.5°C.
